subSection.paragraph:
For studying community patterns of benthic invertebrates, alpine lakes of central Europe provide an ideal study system. They are well-defined small habitats, have similar environmental conditions, and are almost unaffected by human activity. Only a small number of ecological and taxonomic studies have focused on the alpine region ( e.g., Pehofer, 1989 ; Traunspurger, 1996a , b;
Michiels et al., 2004
). Most studies have been restricted to the macrofauna (organisms which are retained on a net with a mesh size of 500 µ m), while the meiofauna (organisms which are retained on a net with a mesh size of about 40 µ m) has received less attention; moreover, much less is known of the most abundant and species rich taxa – the nematodes.

The calculation of nematode biomass was based on Andrássy (1956) . Males, females, and two categories of juveniles (stages 4 and 1-3) were treated separately. For all other invertebrates 20 individuals per taxon and per lake were measured (body length, diam.) to the nearest µ m, using calibrated Zeiss image analysis software (KS300 3.0). Body volume of ostracods, copepods, gastrotrichs, tardigrades and oligochaetes was derived from measurements using the formula of Feller and Warwick (1992). Rotifers were assumed to be ellipsoid/oval ( Herzig, 1984 ). Their body volume was multiplied by an average density (1.13 g/cm 3 ) and a dry/wet ratio of 0.25 to obtain dry weight biomass (
Danovaro et al. , 2002
). For chironomids and nauplii (Crustacea: Copepoda), measurements were converted to dry weight using published regression equations (
Stead et al. , 2003
).

